href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>P \in \mathcal {D}</fr:tex> be a <fr:link
href="jms-004B.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004B">positive</fr:link> object in a <fr:link
href="jms-004S.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004S">negatively univalent deductive system</fr:link>; then the type of <fr:link
href="jms-004M.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004M">upshift structures</fr:link> on <fr:tex>P</fr:tex> is a proposition. In this case, we may refer to the property of <fr:tex>P</fr:tex> <fr:em>having an upshift</fr:em>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>11548</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-004X</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>Let <fr:tex>f_0:M_0 \vdash  P</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>f_1:M_1 \vdash  P</fr:tex> be two <fr:link
href="jms-004M.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004M">upshift structures</fr:link> on <fr:tex>P</fr:tex>, whose inverse delay maps are written <fr:tex>d_0,d_1</fr:tex> respectively. We wish to identify the pairs <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( M_0,f_0 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( M_1,f_1 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>All four maps <fr:tex>f_0,f_1,d_0,d_1</fr:tex> are linear: the forcing maps are linear by definition, and the delay maps are linear because they come from a positive object. Thus we have a linearly invertible linear map <fr:tex>f_1;d_0 : M_1 \vdash  M_0</fr:tex>; because <fr:tex>\mathcal {D}</fr:tex> is assumed <fr:link
href="jms-004S.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004S">negatively univalent</fr:link>, we may identify the pairs <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( M_0, 1 _{ M_0 }  : M_0 \vdash  M_0 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( M_1, { \mathopen {} \left ( f_1;d_0 : M_1 \vdash  M_0 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>. Precomposing with <fr:tex>f_0 : M_0 \vdash  P</fr:tex> in both sides, we have <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( M_0,f_0 \right ) \mathclose {}}  =  { \mathopen {} \left ( M_1,f_1 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> because <fr:tex>d_0</fr:tex> is linear as a map out of a positive object.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
